## What the control plane does

A Paperclip/HQ-style control plane turns agent work into durable company state.

It should track:

- company goals;
- projects;
- agents;
- issues/tasks;
- approvals;
- activity;
- costs;
- comments;
- artifacts;
- plugin events.

Without this layer, agents produce scattered chats. With it, work has an owner, status, proof, and review path.

## Local/private deployment principle

For early personal agentic companies, local/private deployment is safer:

- avoid exposing admin UI publicly;
- keep secrets out of public config;
- use authenticated local access;
- verify health endpoints;
- backup database and object storage deliberately;
- treat deletion features as dangerous.

## Health check concept

A control plane should expose or support checks like:

```bash
systemctl --user is-active paperclipai.service
curl -fsS http://127.0.0.1:3100/api/health
curl -fsSI http://127.0.0.1:3100
paperclipai --version
```

Adapt paths and service names to your install.

## Company model

Starter company fields:

```yaml
name: Galyarder Labs
mission: Turn human intent, memory, decisions, research, engineering, operations, and documentation into delegated agent workflows.
operating_principle: Human command, agent execution, approval gates, evidence trail.
```

## Agent roster

Start with coordination before specialists:

1. Chief of Staff — queue, priorities, blockers, daily pulse;
2. CTO — architecture and implementation;
3. Product/UX — requirements and interface quality;
4. Research — sources and market intelligence;
5. Documentation — canon, guides, release notes;
6. Operations — process, access, maintenance;
7. Growth/DevRel — distribution and content.

Do not create ten agents before you have one useful task loop.

## Task packet

Every task should include:

```md
Objective: why this matters.
Owner: role responsible.
Task: one concrete deliverable.
Inputs: files, links, constraints.
Output format: exact artifact expected.
Success criteria: what makes it good enough.
Review gate: who/what verifies it.
Next action: what happens if accepted.
```

## Approval queues

Use approvals for:

- public communication;
- destructive changes;
- money/spend;
- account permissions;
- production deploys;
- legal/security-sensitive decisions;
- major strategy changes.

## Activity and cost

The system should show:

- recent work;
- stale tasks;
- failed runs;
- cost per agent;
- active blockers;
- pending approvals;
- outputs produced.

This prevents invisible runaway agents.

## Plugin principles

Plugins should be scoped and verified:

- GitHub Issues for repo work;
- Discord for command/notification;
- Telegram for compact alerts;
- Hindsight/Obsidian for memory/notes;
- Linear/Notion for external planning/docs.

Secrets must live in secret storage or private local config. If a plugin forces plaintext tokens, keep it local/private, document the exception, and avoid printing logs.

## Audit log

Every important side effect should be reconstructable:

- who requested it;
- which agent executed;
- what changed;
- what proof exists;
- what approval was used;
- where the artifact lives.
